If you’ve ever stared at an RxJS diagram and thought “I sort of get it, but not really” — this one’s for you.
I’ve been writing Angular for years now, and I still remember the exact moment RxJS clicked for me. It wasn’t from reading the official docs (bless their hearts, those docs are thorough but dense). It was from thinking about how I actually experience media in everyday life — Netflix, radio, Slack, Zoom calls.
Once I mapped those experiences onto RxJS types, everything made sense. The marble diagrams, the operators, the subscriptions — they all fell into place.
So that’s what this post is. A proper tour through every major Observable type, explained through analogies you already live with, backed up by concrete setInterval code examples so you can feel the difference, not just read about it.
Let’s get into it.
The Mental Model You Need First
Before we touch a single line of code, I want you to hold one core question in your mind as we go through each type:
When does the data start flowing, and who gets to see it?
That’s it. Every distinction between Observable types — Cold vs. Hot, Subject vs. BehaviorSubject — boils down to some variation of that question.
1. Cold Observables — The Netflix Model
The Analogy
Think about watching a show on Netflix. When you press play on Breaking Bad, the show starts from Episode 1, Season 1, for you specifically. Your friend can press play at the exact same moment on their own account, and they also start from Episode 1, Season 1 — their own private copy. You’re not watching the same stream. Netflix creates a fresh playback session for every single viewer.
That’s a Cold Observable.

• Data production starts when you subscribe.

• Every subscriber gets their own independent stream.

• Late or early, it doesn’t matter — you always start from the beginning.
Real-World Angular Code
This is the default in Angular. Every time you call HttpClient.get(), you're getting a Cold Observable. The HTTP request doesn't fire until something subscribes to it. Call it twice, you get two separate HTTP requests.
import { of } from 'rxjs';// 'of' is Cold - each subscriber gets their own execution
const cold$ = of(1, 2, 3);
cold$.subscribe(val => console.log('Subscriber A:', val));
cold$.subscribe(val => console.log('Subscriber B:', val));
// Output:
// Subscriber A: 1
// Subscriber A: 2
// Subscriber A: 3
// Subscriber B: 1 <-- B gets its own fresh stream from 1
// Subscriber B: 2
// Subscriber B: 3
The setInterval Test
Here’s where it gets visual. Let’s create a cold interval — a counter that ticks every second.
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';// A manually created Cold Observable - interval created fresh per subscriber
const coldInterval$ = new Observable<number>(observer => {
let count = 0;
const id = setInterval(() => observer.next(count++), 1000);
return () => clearInterval(id); // cleanup on unsubscribe
});
// Subscriber A joins immediately
coldInterval$.subscribe(val => console.log('A:', val));
// Subscriber B joins 2.5 seconds later
setTimeout(() => {
coldInterval$.subscribe(val => console.log('B:', val));
}, 2500);
// Output:
// A: 0 (t=1s)
// A: 1 (t=2s)
// A: 2 (t=3s) <-- B also starts its OWN interval
// B: 0 (t=3s) <-- B starts from 0, completely fresh
// A: 3 (t=4s)
// B: 1 (t=4s)
See that? When Subscriber B joins at 2.5 seconds, it doesn’t jump into the middle of A’s stream. It gets its own setInterval created fresh — starting from 0. This is unicast behaviour. One subscriber, one private stream.
2. Hot Observables — The Live Radio Model
The Analogy
Now imagine tuning into a live FM radio station. The music is playing whether you’re listening or not. You tune in at 3pm and hear whatever song is playing right now. You missed the 10am morning show? Tough luck — it’s gone. You can’t rewind FM radio.
That’s a Hot Observable.

• Data production happens independently of subscribers.

• All subscribers share the same single stream.

• Tune in late and you miss what already played.
Real-World Angular Code
DOM events are the classic example. The click event on a button fires whether you're listening or not. The browser doesn't hold onto previous clicks for new listeners.
import { fromEvent } from 'rxjs';const clicks$ = fromEvent(document, 'click');
// This doesn't trigger any clicks - it just wires up a listener
clicks$.subscribe(e => console.log('Listener A clicked:', e));
WebSockets work the same way. Messages arrive from the server, whether your component has subscribed yet or not.
The setInterval Test
To convert a cold interval into a hot one, we use the share() operator. This is the bridge between the two worlds.
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';
import { share } from 'rxjs/operators';const hotInterval$ = new Observable<number>(observer => {
let count = 0;
const id = setInterval(() => observer.next(count++), 1000);
return () => clearInterval(id);
}).pipe(share()); // <-- This is the magic. One shared execution.
// Subscriber A joins immediately
hotInterval$.subscribe(val => console.log('A:', val));
// Subscriber B joins 2.5 seconds later
setTimeout(() => {
hotInterval$.subscribe(val => console.log('B:', val));
}, 2500);
// Output:
// A: 0 (t=1s)
// A: 1 (t=2s)
// A: 2 (t=3s) <-- B joins, but there's only ONE interval running
// B: 2 (t=3s) <-- B gets the SAME value A gets, not 0!
// A: 3 (t=4s)
// B: 3 (t=4s)
B doesn’t start from 0. B walks into the live stream mid-show. There’s only one setInterval running, and both A and B are tuned into it. This is multicast.
3. Subject — The Voice Call Model
The Analogy
Think of a voice-only Zoom call — no chat, no recording, pure audio. You join at 10:05 am and hear the conversation happening right now. The first 5 minutes when others were warming up? You missed them entirely. Nobody saves audio on a regular Zoom call.
Here’s what makes Zoom a particularly good fit for a Subject: anyone on the call can unmute and speak. It's not a one-way broadcast. Alice unmutes and says something — everyone hears it. Bob unmutes a minute later — everyone hears that too. Each person choosing to unmute and speak is exactly like calling .next() on a Subject. Any participant can push a new value into the stream, and all current subscribers receive it in real time.
That’s a plain Subject.
Real-World Angular Code
Subjects are great for simple event buses — broadcasting something happened across unrelated components.
import { Subject } from 'rxjs';const eventBus$ = new Subject<string>();
// Component A subscribes
eventBus$.subscribe(msg => console.log('Component A got:', msg));
// Somewhere else in your app, you push events
eventBus$.next('user-logged-in');
eventBus$.next('cart-updated');
// Component B subscribes AFTER events were emitted
eventBus$.subscribe(msg => console.log('Component B got:', msg));
eventBus$.next('checkout-completed'); // Both A and B get this one
// Output:
// Component A got: user-logged-in
// Component A got: cart-updated
// Component A got: checkout-completed
// Component B got: checkout-completed <-- B missed the first two entirely
The setInterval Test
import { Subject } from 'rxjs';const subject$ = new Subject<number>();
// Feed values in via setInterval
let count = 0;
setInterval(() => subject$.next(count++), 1000);
// Subscriber A joins immediately
subject$.subscribe(val => console.log('A:', val));
// Subscriber B joins at 2.5 seconds
setTimeout(() => {
console.log('B is joining now...');
subject$.subscribe(val => console.log('B:', val));
}, 2500);
// Output:
// A: 0 (t=1s)
// A: 1 (t=2s)
// B is joining now...
// <-- B sits in silence, waiting. No history replayed.
// A: 2 (t=3s)
// B: 2 (t=3s) <-- B's first value ever. It waited for the next natural tick.
// A: 3 (t=4s)
// B: 3 (t=4s)
B had to sit in silence from 2.5s to 3.0s. It couldn’t get anything until the Subject naturally emitted its next tick. If you need a late subscriber to immediately get something, a plain Subject won’t help you.
4. BehaviorSubject — The Pinned Status Model
The Analogy
You’re added to a team Slack channel that has a pinned “Current Sprint Objective” message at the top. The moment you join, Slack forces that pinned message to your view — you immediately know what the team is focused on, even if everyone went quiet an hour ago.
And just like in a real Slack channel, anyone can send a new message at any time. When someone types and hits Enter, everyone currently in the channel sees it instantly — and that message now becomes the new “latest state” that the next person joining will receive first. That’s .next() in action. Any part of your code can push a fresh value in, it replaces the stored current state, and every subscriber gets the update immediately.
That’s a BehaviorSubject. It always holds the last known value and hands it to any new subscriber the instant they join.
Real-World Angular Code
This is the workhorse of Angular state management. NgRx, Akita, and homegrown state services all use BehaviorSubject under the hood. It's perfect for things like the current authenticated user, a selected theme, or a UI loading flag.
import { BehaviorSubject } from 'rxjs';// Must be initialized with a starting value
const currentUser$ = new BehaviorSubject<string | null>(null);
// User logs in
currentUser$.next('alice@example.com');
// Some component subscribes after the login already happened
currentUser$.subscribe(user => {
console.log('Current user:', user);
// Immediately prints 'alice@example.com' - no waiting.
});
// You can also peek at the current value synchronously
console.log('Snapshot:', currentUser$.getValue()); // 'alice@example.com'
The setInterval Test
import { BehaviorSubject } from 'rxjs';// Must be initialized with a starting value
const behavior$ = new BehaviorSubject<number>(-1); // Initial value: -1
let count = 0;
setInterval(() => behavior$.next(count++), 1000);
// Subscriber A joins immediately
behavior$.subscribe(val => console.log('A:', val));
// Subscriber B joins at 2.5 seconds
setTimeout(() => {
console.log('B is joining now...');
behavior$.subscribe(val => console.log('B:', val));
}, 2500);
// Output:
// A: -1 (immediately - the initial value)
// A: 0 (t=1s)
// A: 1 (t=2s)
// B is joining now...
// B: 1 (t=2.5s - IMMEDIATELY gets the last emitted value, no waiting!)
// A: 2 (t=3s)
// B: 2 (t=3s)
Did you catch that? At 2.5 seconds, B instantly received 1 — the most recent value — without waiting for the next tick at 3.0s. It walked into the room and immediately got caught up on the current state.
This is what makes BehaviorSubject so valuable for state management. New components that subscribe get the current snapshot of state immediately, and then continue receiving updates.
5. ReplaySubject — The Slack History Model
The Analogy
You join a Slack channel for the first time, and instead of seeing an empty screen, Slack immediately downloads the last 50 messages so you can read the context of what’s been discussed. You don’t just know the current state — you get to see the recent history.
And of course, once you’re caught up, the channel keeps going. Anyone in the channel can send a new message — type something and hit Enter, and everyone sees it live. That’s .next(). New messages keep flowing in after the history replay is done, and everyone — old members and newly joined ones alike — receives them in real time.
That’s a ReplaySubject. You configure exactly how many past emissions it should remember and replay to latecomers.
Real-World Angular Code
Use this when context matters — recent chat messages, a history of actions the user has taken, or an audit log of recent state changes.
import { ReplaySubject } from 'rxjs';// Remember the last 3 emissions
const recentMessages$ = new ReplaySubject<string>(3);
recentMessages$.next('Alice: Hey everyone!');
recentMessages$.next('Bob: What time is the meeting?');
recentMessages$.next('Alice: 3pm today');
recentMessages$.next('Charlie: I might be 5 mins late'); // 4th message
